The verb is from {{inh|en|enm|speten|spē̆ten}}, {{m|enm|spete||to spit (blood, phlegm, saliva, venom, etc.); of a fire: to emit sparks}}, from {{inh|en|ang|spǣtan||to spit; to squirt}};<ref>{{R:MED Online|entry=spē̆ten|pos=v|id=MED42169|accessdate=21 March 2019}}</ref> or from {{inh|en|enm|spit}}, {{m|enm|spitte}}, {{m|enm|spitten||to spit (blood, phlegm, saliva, venom, etc.); of a fire: to emit sparks}}, from {{inh|en|ang|spittan}}, {{m|ang|sypttan||to spit}},<ref>{{R:MED Online|entry=spitten|pos=''v.''(1)|noformat=yes|id=MED42279|date=21 March 2019}}</ref><ref name="OED v2">{{R:OED Online|pos=''v.{{sup|2}}''|noformat=yes|id=186975|date=1914}}</ref> both from {{inh|en|gem-pro|-}}, from {{inh|en|ine-pro|*sp(y)ēw}}, {{m|ine-pro|*spyū}},<ref>{{cite-book|author=John Ayto|title=Dictionary of Word Origins|location=New York, N.Y.|publisher=Arcade Publishing|year=1990|isbn=978-1-55970-133-4}}.</ref> ultimately {{glossary|imitative}}; compare {{cog|enm|spitelen||to spit out, expectorate}}<ref>{{R:MED Online|entry=spitelen|pos=v|id=MED42267|accessdate=21 March 2019|nodot=yes}}, derived from {{cog|enm|spitten}}.</ref> and {{cog|en|spew}}.<ref>{{R:Online Etymology Dictionary}}</ref> The English word is cognate with {{cog|da|spytte||to spit}}, {{cog|frr|spütte}}, {{cog|no|spytte||to spit}}, {{cog|sv|spotta||to spit}}, {{cog|non|spýta}} ({{cog|fo|spýta||to spit}}, {{cog|is|spýta||to spit}}).<ref name="OED v2"/>

